05424nam a22008415i 9780231549349DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018048958  a97802315493497 a10.7312/ayub191322doi  a(DE-B1597)526880  a(OCoLC)1104716592  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBP134.S49bA98 2019 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a297.50812231 aAyubi, Zahra M. S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGendered Morality :bClassical Islamic Ethics of the Self, Family, and Society /cZahra M. S. Ayubi. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE. Epistemology and Gender Analytics of Islamic Ethics -- tCHAPTER TWO. Gendered Metaphysics, Perfection, and Power of the (Hu)man’s Soul -- tCHAPTER THREE. Ethics of Marriage and the Domestic Economy -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Homosocial Masculinity and Societal Ethics -- tConclusion. Prolegomenon to Feminist Philosophy of Islam -- tGlossary of Persian and Arabic Terms -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIslamic scriptural sources offer potentially radical notions of equality. Yet medieval Islamic philosophers chose to establish hierarchical, male-centered virtue ethics. In Gendered Morality, Zahra Ayubi rethinks the tradition of Islamic philosophical ethics from a feminist critical perspective. She calls for a philosophical turn in the study of gender in Islam based on resources for gender equality that are unlocked by feminist engagement with the Islamic ethical tradition.Developing a lens for a feminist philosophy of Islam, Ayubi analyzes constructions of masculinity, femininity, and gender relations in classic works of philosophical ethics. In close readings of foundational texts by Abu Hamid Muhammad al-Ghazali, Nasir-ad Din Tusi, and Jalal ad-Din Davani, she interrogates how these thinkers conceive of the ethical human being as an elite male within a hierarchical cosmology built on the exclusion of women and nonelites. Yet in the course of prescribing ethical behavior, the ethicists speak of complex gendered and human relations that contradict their hierarchies. Their metaphysical premises about the nature of the divine, humanity, and moral responsibility indicate a potential egalitarian core. Gendered Morality offers a vital and disruptive new perspective on patriarchal Islamic ethics and metaphysics, showing the ways in which the philosophical tradition can support the aims of gender justice and human flourishing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFemininityxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aIslamxSocial aspects. 0aIslamic philosophy. 0aMarriagexReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aMasculinityxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aReligion and social status. 0aSex rolexReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aSocial ethicsxReligious aspectsxIslam. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig. Stud., Jewish Stud.2019 Englishz978311061074108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Relig. Studies, Jewish Studies 2019z9783110606508oZDB-23-DGF40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/ayub1913240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978